06666nam a22010455i 9781501509445DE-B159720211217065530.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||211217t20182006gw     fo  d z      eng d  a97815015094457 a10.1515/97815015094452doi  a(DE-B1597)493378  a(OCoLC)1076803685  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  agwcDE 4aQE367.2b.N48 2006 7aSCI0480002bisacsh04a552/.0622300aNeutron Scattering in Earth Sciences /ced. by Hans Rudolf Wenk. 1aBerlin ;aBoston : bDe Gruyter, c[2018] 4cÂ©2006  a1 online resource (XX, 471 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aReviews in Mineralogy & Geochemistry ,x1529-6466 ;v630 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aVolume 63 of Reviews in Mineralogy and Geochemistry provides an introduction for those not yet familiar with neutrons by describing basic features of neutrons and their interaction with matter as well illustrating important applications. The volume is divided into 17 Chapters. The first two chapters introduce properties of neutrons and neutron facilities, setting the stage for applications. Some applications rely on single crystals (Chapter 3) but mostly powders (Chapters 4-5) and bulk polycrystals (Chapters 15-16) are analyzed, at ambient conditions as well as low and high temperature and high pressure (Chapters 7-9). Characterization of magnetic structures remains a core application of neutron scattering (Chapter 6). The analysis of neutron data is not trivial and crystallographic methods have been modified to take account of the complexities, such as the Rietveld technique (Chapter 4) and the pair distribution function (Chapter 11). Information is not only obtained about solids but about liquids, melts and aqueous solutions as well (Chapters 11-13). In fact this field, approached with inelastic scattering (Chapter 10) and small angle scattering (Chapter 13) is opening unprecedented opportunities for earth sciences. Small angle scattering also contributes information about microstructures (Chapter 14). Neutron diffraction has become a favorite method to quantify residual stresses in deformed materials (Chapter 16) as well as preferred orientation patterns (Chapter 15). The volume concludes with a short introduction into neutron tomography and radiography that may well emerge as a principal application of neutron scattering in the future (Chapter 17).  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 17. Dez 2021) 0aGeophysicsxMethodology. 0aMineralogy, Determinative. 0aNeutronsxDiffraction. 0aNeutronsxInelastic scattering. 4aGeowissenschaften. 4aKongress. 4aNeutronenstreuung. 7aSCIENCE / Earth Sciences / Mineralogy.2bisacsh1 aBenmore, Chris J., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCole, David R., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDaymond, Mark R., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDepmeier, Wulf, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHansen, Thomas C., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHarrison, Richard J., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHerwig, Kenneth W., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHoffmann, Christina, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKnorr, Karsten, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKuhs, Werner F., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLarese, John Z., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLoong, Chun-Keung, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMamontov, Eugene, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 